B5(shp)
list is official (meaning it stays as it and does not change over time unless in extreme circumstances)
names like ‘JOAn’ etc, can be just about anything
There are two types of names
1 that apply to the strict rules of the language and the stress is the same as in the language
2 ones that are kept exactly the same as they are in their native language and all the word stress remains the same
all the second type of words start with a ‘shput’ and then followed by the name. For example, shput-sandy OR shput-Lili
The letters after the ‘sh^R’ can be written with whichever writing system the speaker chooses but it is intended that they use the same writing system the script came from.
For example, if the name is European, then write it out with the Roman alphabet, if the name is Chinese, write it out with the Chinese character to represent that name.
this trick can also be used for when naming words that do exist in another language (or that you only know the term for it in your native lang) e.g. pr-computer
In order to show tence for such names (ones that are not offical), you need the following official word word that attached to a word [meaning any descriptions (e.g. tense, descriptions marnets etc) applied to this word will apply to that word] g L a m
If a name appears at the next word directly after ‘Glam’ it takes the same word form as what the ‘glam’ word form is
